                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">What We&#8217;re Reading</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By The New York Times                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-07-14T21:05:26+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 14, 2015 5:05 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 14, 2015 5:05 pm</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/14/what-were-reading-72/" data-title="What We&#8217;re Reading" data-description="Get recommendations from New York Times reporters and editors, highlighting interesting stories from around the web. In this installment, great reads from Vanessa Friedman, Tom Redburn and others. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Get recommendations from New York Times reporters and editors, highlighting great stories from around the web. What Weâre Reading emails are sent twice a week.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><iframe title="regilite" height="120" scrolling="no" src="https://regilite.nytimes.com/regilite?product=WWRO&amp;theme=Transparent&amp;landing=true" width="450"></iframe></p>
</div>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/RedburnHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>The New Yorker</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.newyorker.com/news/john-cassidy/a-humiliating-deal-for-greece?intcid=mod-latest">Debating Greece&#8217;s Deal</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There&#8217;s a striking debate going on at The New Yorker. On one side, John Cassidy makes the case for why the deal for Greece, reflecting Germany&#8217;s ruthless display of power, is a nightmare that will haunt Europe for years. On the other, <a href="//www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/greece-needs-the-euro?intcid=mod-latest">Bernard Avishai argues that Greece is making the right choice</a> by remaining in the eurozone, despite Germany&#8217;s harsh discipline, because small countries need a stable currency to integrate into the global economy. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/TomRedburn">â Tom Redburn</a></p>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/ChangHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>The Planetary Society</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/">Hello, Pluto</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like the people working on the NASA spacecraft that <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/15/science/space/nasa-new-horizons-spacecraft-reaches-pluto.html">zipped by Pluto</a> today, I&#8217;m happy the wait is over. I first wrote about Pluto almost 20 years ago, in a feature story for the San Diego Union-Tribune. That&#8217;s so long ago that you can&#8217;t find it on the web. For people who are interested in more of the geeky geological details (in an eminently and entertainingly readable way), check out the blog of Emily Lakdawalla at the Planetary Society. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/kchangnyt">â Kenneth Chang</a></p>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/SiftonHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>GQ</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.gq.com/story/food-and-life?src=longreads">Pay It Forward</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those interested in the restorative power of pleasure may get a kick out of Brett Martin&#8217;s memoir of meeting Jacques Pepin for the first time, and how the chef unwittingly helped bring him back from the edge of a very bad breakup. Itâs a fine rumination on the role good food and wine can play in our lives. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/SamSifton">â Sam Sifton</a></p>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/SantosHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>Bloomberg Business</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-07/a-new-york-pizza-man-s-brazil-nightmare-and-the-mess-it-exposed">Bad for Business</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Through the story of one man, this piece describes the weight of bureaucracy in the world of small business in Brazil, Latin America&#8217;s largest economy. It&#8217;s an experience I know well: I&#8217;m from Brazil and several of my relatives there are small-business owners. During construction of a luncheonette Salvador, an uncle, opened in my hometown, he said: &#8220;I&#8217;d give up had I not invested all the money I had in this business.&#8221; Red tape is pervasive in Brazil and, as this piece shows, a significant impediment to economic growth. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/FernandaNYT">â Fernanda Santos</a></p>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/StallmanHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>The California Sunday Magazine</h5>
<h4><a href="https://stories.californiasunday.com/2015-07-05/the-everlasting-forrest-fenn/">Gold Digger</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There&#8217;s a treasure buried âin the mountains somewhere north of Santa Fe.â This is the story of the man who put it there, Forrest Fenn, an eccentric writer and gallerist who seems tickled to sit back and watch treasure hunters of the world try, and so far fail, to crack his poetic code.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Begin it where warm waters halt<br />
And take it in the canyon down,<br />
Not far, but too far to walk.<br />
Put in below the home of Brown.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read the article. Absorb the poem. Go find the fortune. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/NYTSports">â Jason Stallman</a></p>
<div class="w50 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/FriedmanHead.png" alt="" /></div>
<h5>The New Yorker</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/07/20/the-actual-hollister">Roots</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is one of the best pieces I&#8217;ve read about the way fashion can distort reality, and about its often unforeseen moral effects. It turns out Dave Eggers, the author, has a great-great-grandfather who founded a town in California called Hollister, a name that was appropriated, coincidentally or not, by Abercrombie &amp; Fitch for one of its subsidiary brands. Many of us probably know this because the name is displayed on shirts and hoodies everywhere. Mr. Eggers goes back to find out the truth, which is a lot more depressing and complicated (and interesting) than any ad campaign might make you imagine. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/vvfriedman">â Vanessa Friedman</a></p>
</div>
